📝 Observations
Across all four supervised learning models applied to the Heart Disease Prediction dataset,
several key observations can be drawn. The Decision Tree achieved the highest overall accuracy
of 86.96%, making it the strongest performer in terms of raw classification performance while
also offering the advantage of visual interpretability through its tree structure, which allows
anyone to follow the exact path of decisions the model makes. Within the Decision Tree,
ST_Slope and ChestPainType emerged as the most dominant features, suggesting that the slope
of the ST segment during exercise and the type of chest pain a patient experiences are the
strongest clinical indicators of heart disease in this dataset. Despite being technically
unsuitable for binary classification problems, Linear Regression still managed a reasonable
accuracy of 83.70% when predictions were thresholded at 0.5, however its residual plot
confirms that it struggles to model a binary outcome correctly since predictions frequently
fall outside the natural 0–1 range, which is why Logistic Regression exists as its proper
replacement for classification tasks. Naïve Bayes achieved the highest AUC-ROC score of
0.9090, meaning that despite its simplifying assumption that all features are independent
of each other, it was the most reliable model at separating patients with and without heart
disease across all possible classification thresholds, which is a remarkable result given
how strong that independence assumption is in practice. Finally, Logistic Regression proved
to be the most balanced and clinically meaningful model overall, combining a solid accuracy
of 84.24% with well-calibrated probability outputs and an AUC of 0.9010, making it the most
suitable choice for a real medical setting where knowing the actual probability of disease
rather than just a predicted label is essential for supporting informed clinical decisions.
